snippet.textDisplay: i'm sorry that this has nothing to do with hot sauces, wings, etc. but i just needed to rewind a little (i actually paused it just so i could write this comment, lol). it's really important that people understand the effect(s) (positive and negative) of when terms like "chinaman" are used. i'm not trying to defend harry carey (yes, i know who he was and have actually heard him use other "terms" to describe other races and if anyone is curious, i'm Asian born and raised in Canada) but he is of a different time. i probably would've been offended (in my younger days) and maybe i'm focusing on other things now but people seem to forget other aspects. was carey a racist (or others) because he dropped "terms" like that in a seemingly innocent way where no sick hate was intended? it's possible for me to say no. but he's definitely ignorant and very possibly resistant to change. which is not only omnipresent but seemingly increasing almost exponentially. but the reason i'm writing this is that will ferrell heard that (and i can only imagine he heard the same one(s) i've heard from carey in the past) and clearly he knew there was at least something amiss, if not something that could be "missed by the censors". and it got me thinking about the recipient of the "message". now, i don't know will ferrell, i'm not a huge fan but i do like some of his movies (actually he's in one movie that's in my all-time top 5) but he doesn't exactly come off (at least to me) as a racist or someone with racist undertones. but he understood the "harry carey-type" (in fact, when he heard that, i'm sure we had similar reactions while we were processing what we heard on live tv) which probably helped him form his character for his auditions and later use to increase his material catalog. again, i'm not trying to dismiss or defend the "harry carey-type". but, at some point (even back in the 80s, that's when i first heard about harry carey and his..."antics") during his life, he must've been approached either at work or in his personal life that some of his racially themed comments were inappropriate or possibly offensive. again, i'm not professing to know harry carey, but generally speaking, people are resistant to change. also, the older you get...things aren't as easy and adapting to change is not in our nature (which is kind of ironic...omnipresent, remember? maybe our inability to adapt to change is our ultimate demise, which is kind of general, sorry.). either way, i'm wiling to bet that he was approached and ultimately kept thinking that anyone with black hair, yellow complexion, almond shaped eyes, etc. are from China (and while trying to spin this in a humours way, with about 1 billion of them, at least when carey was alive, the numbers were in his favour) or in his mind (and to be sincere, regarding other races he was terribly narrow minded, partly due to his ignorance, but really that can be said about everyone in his case) that's the only country he needs to remember regarding people that "look like that". i'm not sure if that tiny little part of the clip was intentionally kept in, forgotten about while editing, maybe the producers/editors grew up with the term and due to their own ignorance kept it in...i'm not trying to defend or attack any one or side. i just thought it was very interesting (thought-provoking? clearly comment-writing provoking). yeah, those are dangerous, hurtful, whatever you want to consider them but there's much more to it than that. it's not only the word, term, phrase, but also where/who it's coming from, who/where it's directed to, the level of malice...the list goes on. perhaps we've always done this but we just react. we don't stop to think and analyze. maybe this fast moving world doesn't want us to do that because "control" is better when it's not focused on, so we focus on other things (i'll stop there on that b/c that's just...moving on). i'm encouraged that ferrell had enough in his brain to pause when he heard carey's comments. but, i'm dismayed that someone could interpret that as, "well the term chinaman has been used for decades, and by prominent people" or something to that affect. have i been called that? yes. m'i being attacked or feel like it? sure. but i didn't want to focus on me. i wanted to focus on my "attacker" or the "harry carey-type" or really any run-of-the-mill racist. whether you attend meetings and share your racist views with like-minded people or keep them to yourselves in your mind, it's not something you can endure or preserve. do i want those terms banned or something and you get a fine or something for saying them, no because that sounds ridiculous (at least to me). what needs to be done, is being done. without getting to even more details, and in retrospect i guess i could've said this mostly and i wouldn't have had to type all this out, but life changes. it's all about change. and when you don't change, you die. please, please know that i do not mean that as a threat. if there is some master plan for all the races, i don't know what it is. i just meant, if you don't adapt to changes, at the very least, you will become obsolete, redundant, basically left behind. i'm not saying there is no racism in this world today. i hope i'm not that naive. what i am saying is that eventually (hopefully before the universe collapses on itself) there will be no racism in this world again. the level of one's adaptation to change (no matter how minuscule or massive) will dictate humanity's survival. but i am willing to bet that humanity will rid itself of our racism. and when that day arrives (again before the universe collapses on itself), i sincerely hope it will be quite a spectacle for that one person left on earth watching the universe collapse on itself.
